body:
I think it is bad that when you use "//" to generate a html comment jade will add a whitespace before "-->".

I would change this:

```
parseComment: function(){
    var str = this.expect('comment').val;
    return "buf.push('<!--" + str + " -->')";
},
```

to:

```
parseComment: function(){
    var str = this.expect('comment').val;
    return "buf.push('<!--" + str + "-->')";
},
```

...As you can see I just removed the whitespace.

Why do I think this is necessary?
If I would like to generate someting like this through jade (dont think it is possible when jade adding the whitespace):

<!--[if lt IE 7 ]> <body class="ie6"> <![endif]--> 

<!--[if IE 7 ]>    <body class="ie7"> <![endif]--> 

<!--[if IE 8 ]>    <body class="ie8"> <![endif]--> 

<!--[if IE 9 ]>    <body class="ie9"> <![endif]--> 

<!--[if gt IE 9]>  <body> <![endif]-->

<!--[if !IE]><!--> <body> <!--<![endif]-->

this example code is from: http://paulirish.com/2008/conditional-stylesheets-vs-css-hacks-answer-neither/
